  "prompt": "Can a Roman Catholic boy from Kerala marry a Hindu girl from another state?",
  "response": "Yes, a Roman Catholic boy from Kerala can marry a Hindu girl from another state. Interfaith marriages are legally permitted in India under the Special Marriage Act of 1954. This act allows individuals of different religions to marry without converting to each other's religion. Both parties must meet certain requirements, such as being of legal age (at least 21 years for the groom and 18 years for the bride), consenting to the marriage, and not having a living spouse from a previous marriage.\n\nThe couple will need to give notice of the marriage to the Marriage Registrar in the area where one of them has resided for at least 30 days prior to the notice. After a 30-day waiting period, during which objections to the marriage can be raised, the marriage can be solemnized.\n\nIt's important to recognize that while the legal framework supports such marriages, the couple might face social or familial challenges, depending on their personal and community dynamics. Open communication with family members and seeking support from friends or community groups can be helpful in navigating these challenges.",
